{"id":"Q11705","names":{"en":"Rashidun Caliphate","tr":"Râşidûn Halifeleri","ar":"al-Khulafā' al-Rāshidūn"},"country":["BH","EG","IQ","IR","PS","SA","SY","YE"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":632,"extinct":661},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"1","atlas_name_en_original":"The Rightly-Guided or 'Patriarchal' or 'Orthodox' Caliphs","parent_tribe":"Quraysh","ethnic_origin":"Arap","capital":"Medine (Medina); Kûfe (Kūfa) (Ali döneminde)","region_primary":"Hicaz - Medine (Medina)","regions_all":"Hicaz; Suriye; Filistin; Mısır; Irak; İran; Bahreyn; Umman; Yemen","geographic_zone":"Arap Yarımadası","predecessor":"Hz. Muhammed (Peygamber dönemi)","successor":"Emevî Halifeleri","government_type":"Hilafet","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Rashidun Caliphate represents the founding political order of the Islamic community after Prophet Muhammad's death, dismantling the Sasanian Empire entirely and expelling Byzantium from Syria and Egypt within three decades. Abu Bakr secured Arabian unity through the Ridda Wars, while Umar transformed the conquests into a systematic state apparatus. Uthman standardized the Quranic text, but the civil strife (fitna) under Ali created the defining political fracture in Islamic history.","importance_level":"Yüksek","capital_lat":"24.47","capital_lon":"39.61","century_start":7,"century_end":7}}
{"id":"royal-tree:islamic-atlas:40","names":{"en":"Carmathian","tr":"Karmatîler (Ebû Saîdî kolu)","ar":"al-Qarāmita (Āl Abī Sa'īd al-Jannābī)"},"country":["BH","IQ","IR","OM","SA","SY"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":1078},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"40","atlas_name_en_original":"The Carmathian or Qarmati Rulers of the line of Abū Sa'īd al-Jannābī","parent_tribe":"İsmâilî mezhep hareketi","ethnic_origin":"Arap (çeşitli)","capital":"al-Ahsā (Lahsā)","region_primary":"Doğu Arabistan (al-Ahsā / Bahreyn)","regions_all":"al-Ahsā; Bahreyn; Güney Irak (geçici); Suriye sınırı (geçici); Umân (geçici)","geographic_zone":"Arap Yarımadası","predecessor":null,"successor":"Uyûnîler (Banū Murra)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":"Şiî","narrative_en":"The Qarmatians represented the most radical branch of Ismaili Shiism, a militant movement that shook the Islamic world by stealing the Black Stone from the Kaaba. Their egalitarian community model established in eastern Arabia, while controversial, constituted one of the most provocative experiments in Islamic political thought.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"25.38","capital_lon":"49.59","century_start":9,"century_end":11}}
